05000nam a22008895i 9780823254675DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232546757 a10.1515/97808232546752doi  a(DE-B1597)555480  a(OCoLC)1155931464  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBD581b.F65 2013 7aREL0490002bisacsh04a1132231 aFoltz, Bruce V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Noetics of Nature :bEnvironmental Philosophy and the Holy Beauty of the Visible /cBruce V. Foltz. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGroundworks: Ecological Issues in Philosophy and Theology00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Noetics of Nature -- t1. Whence the Depth of Deep Ecology? -- t2. Nature's Other Side -- t3. Layers of Nature in Thomas Traherne and John Muir -- t4. Sailing to Byzantium -- t5. The Resurrection of Nature -- t6. The Iconic Earth -- t7. Seeing Nature -- t8. Seeing God in All Things -- t9. The Glory of God Hidden in Creation -- t10. Between Heaven and Earth -- t11. Nature and Other Modern Idolatries -- t12. Traces of Divine Fragrance, Droplets of Divine Love -- tNotes -- tIndex of Terms in Greek, German, and Latin -- tIndex of Names and Places 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aContemplative or "noetic" knowledge has traditionally been seen as the highest mode of understanding, a view that persists both in many non-Western cultures and in Eastern Christianity, where "theoria physike," or the illumined understanding of creation that follows the purification of the heart, is seen to provide deeper insights into nature than the discursive rationality modernity has used to dominate and conquer it.Working from texts in Eastern Orthodox philosophy and theology not widely known in the West, as well as a variety of sources including mystics such as the Sufi Ibn 'Arabi, poets such as Basho, Traherne, Blake, Hölderlin, and Hopkins, and nature writers such as Muir, Thoreau, and Dillard, The Noetics of Nature challenges both the primacy of the natural sciences in environmental thought and the conventional view, first advanced by Lynn White, Jr., that Christian theology is somehow responsible for the environmental crisis.Instead, Foltz concludes that the ancient Christian view of creation as iconic-its "holy beauty" manifesting the divine energies and constituting a primal mode of divine revelation-offers the best prospect for the radical reversal that is needed in our relation to the natural environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAesthetics. 0aEnvironmental ethics. 0aHuman ecologyxReligious aspects. 0aNaturexReligious aspects. 0aPhilosophy of nature. 4aByzantine and Russian Philosophy. 4aEastern Orthodox Philosophy and Theology. 4aEco-criticism. 4aEco-theology. 4aEcology. 4aEnvironmental Aesthetics. 4aEnvironmental Philosophy. 4aEnvironmental Studies. 4aIntellectual History. 4abyzantine philosophy. 4acreation. 4aenvironment. 4anature. 4aphilosophy of nature. 4arussian philosophy. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Orthodox.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823254675zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823254675423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823254675.jpg  a978-3-11-070729-8  FUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBK